= Introduction

#include "introduction.typ"

Rather than following only fixed instructions, many modern AI systems use algorithms that learn from data. This branch of AI is known as *machine learning*. Instead of programmers specifying every possible rule, machine learning models identify patterns within large datasets and improve their performance over time.

Another important area is *deep learning*, which uses artificial neural networks inspired by the structure of the human brain. Deep learning has enabled major breakthroughs in areas such as image recognition, speech processing, language translation, and autonomous vehicles.

Although AI can perform impressive tasks, it does not possess human consciousness or emotions. Instead, it analyzes information and produces results based on mathematical models and statistical patterns.

== Types of Artificial Intelligence

AI can generally be divided into three categories.

*Narrow AI* is designed to perform specific tasks. Most AI systems in use today belong to this category. Examples include spam filters, navigation systems, facial recognition software, and virtual assistants.

*General AI* refers to a hypothetical system capable of understanding and performing any intellectual task that a human can accomplish. Such systems do not yet exist and remain an active area of research.

*Superintelligent AI* is a theoretical concept describing AI that would surpass human intelligence in nearly every field. While widely discussed in academic and philosophical contexts, it remains speculative.

== Applications of AI in Daily Life

Many people use AI without realizing it. Smartphones use AI to improve photographs, recognize speech, predict text while typing, and organize digital content. Search engines employ AI to rank results based on relevance, while online stores recommend products based on previous purchases and browsing history.

Streaming platforms analyze viewing habits to recommend movies, television shows, and music that users are likely to enjoy. Navigation applications calculate the fastest routes by analyzing traffic conditions in real time. Email services automatically detect spam and prioritize important messages using AI-powered algorithms.

Financial institutions use AI to detect fraudulent transactions, while customer service departments employ chatbots that answer common questions around the clock. These examples demonstrate how AI quietly improves convenience and efficiency in everyday activities.

